univariate - one variable

categorical

examine the distribution of the cut of a diamond

table(dsmall$cut)
## 
##      Fair      Good Very Good   Premium     Ideal 
##        27        83       226       277       387

turn this into a bar chart

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=cut)) + geom_bar()

what if I forgot to put the () after the geometry?

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=cut)) + geom_bar
## Error: Don't know how to add geom_bar to a plot

Interlude: Get rid of bars that show missing data.

Make some missing data in dsmall data set - create a copy for demo purposes

dsmall2 <- dsmall
# random sample of 100 rows, set cut to missing
dsmall2$cut[sample(nrow(dsmall), 100)] <- NA 

ggplot(dsmall2, aes(x=cut)) + geom_bar()

option 1 to remove that bar: subset the data to be plotted to remove NAs

take dsmall, and only the rows where cut is not missing (!is.na()) the ! negates is.na(), so TRUE means the value for cut IS NOT missing.

temp.data.to.plot <- dsmall[!is.na(dsmall$cut),]
ggplot(temp.data.to.plot, aes(x=cut)) + geom_bar()

pie charts can be done, but not recommended without further modification. See the full data viz tutorial for more info.

pie(table(dsmall$cut))

continuous

examine the distribution of the depth of a diamond

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=depth)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

can control the size of the bins by providing an argument to the histogram layer.

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=depth)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 2)

Density plot instead

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=depth)) + geom_density()

histogram + density

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=depth)) + geom_histogram() +  geom_density(col="red")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=depth)) + geom_density(col="red") +  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  • we have to specify that the histogram layer has a different aestetic structure.
  • We tell the histogram layer to plot the density of the data on the y axis, not the count.
  • the .. double dots around density indicate this is a variable that is internally calculated.
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=depth)) + geom_density(col="red") +  
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), colour="black", fill=NA)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

boxplots

For one variable - easier done in base graphics

boxplot(dsmall$depth)

add some critical information so we know what this plot is about. And lets turn this horizontal

boxplot(dsmall$price, horizontal = TRUE, main="Distribution of diamond prices", xlab="Dollars")

bar charts!

  • the second variable is included as a fill color
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=cut, fill=color)) + geom_bar()

  • default is a stacked bar chart kinda hard to read
  • alternative is to create a side by side bar chart add a position argument to the geom_bar() layer
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=cut, fill=color)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge")

  • this demonstrates comparing color within cut.
  • how can we change the above code to commpare CUT within Color?
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=color, fill=cut)) + geom_bar(position = "dodge")

Continuous vs continuous

  • now we define what variable is on the x AND what variable is on the y axis
  • add a trend line using geom_smooth()
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

  • other options for this trend line include:
# 1 fitting a linear model line 
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm")

why not just use geom_line() this connects the dots directly

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_point() + geom_line()

What happens if you remove the geom_point() layer? 

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, y=price)) + geom_line()

cat ~ quanti

  • grouped boxplots
    • y axis here is our continuous variable
    • x is the categorical
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=color, y=carat)) + geom_boxplot()

what if I want horizontal? can i switch x & y?

ggplot(dsmall, aes(y=color, x=carat)) + geom_boxplot()
## Warning: position_dodge requires non-overlapping x intervals

This method didnt work!

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=color, y=carat)) + geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()

  • lets add some colors!
  • color by categorical variable
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=color, y=carat, col=color)) + geom_boxplot() 

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=color, y=carat, fill=color)) + geom_boxplot()

  • now add a violin
# boxplots first, add violin on top - hides the boxes
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=color, y=carat, fill=color)) + geom_boxplot() + geom_violin()

# violins first
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=color, y=carat, fill=color)) + geom_violin() + geom_boxplot()

Neither option is pretty good. so well clean it up by controlling the transparency using alpha, which ranges from 0 -1, and also shrink the width of the boxes.

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=color, y=carat, fill=color)) +
        geom_violin(alpha=.1) + 
        geom_boxplot(alpha=.5, width=.2)

grouped histograms

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, fill=color)) + geom_density()

not readable due to overlap

  • remedy by
  • change alpha /transparency
  • use color instead of fill
ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, col=color)) + geom_density()

ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, fill=color)) + geom_density(alpha=.2)

interlude : putting plots side by side

Plots are just objects. so save them as objects. Use the grid.arrange function inside the gridExtra package to arrange the plots. - first plot a, then b, in 2 columns

library(gridExtra)
a <- ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, fill=color)) + geom_histogram()
b <- ggplot(dsmall, aes(x=carat, fill=color)) + geom_density() 
grid.arrange(a,b, ncol=2)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

other interlude: what is that notation gridExtra::grid.arrange

If you want to call a function without having to load the entire package.

package::function

  • useful especially when using dplyr the filter and select , recode functions overlap/conflict with same named functions in other packages.

  • red flag warning: if youre convinced you loaded a library for a function, but R keeps saying function does not exist? likely a package conflict.
